UML:TaggedValue.value: Collection of utilities that have not attained formal governance status, though in some cases they are on a standardization track. These are recommended best practice within the HollowWorld modelling framework.
Classes corresponding to types and elements provided by GML that do not simply implement existing ISO 19100 classes from the Harmonized Model. See ISO 19136 Annex D.3.
These profiles are extensions of OGC or ISO standard models.
These profiles are extensions of OGC or ISO standard models.

Extensions to ISO 19107 Spatial Schema (implemented as GML Geometry schema), primarily dealing with simplified representations of some simple solids, surfaces and curves.
Documented in OGC 07-001

Extensions to ISO 19123 CV packages, primarily adding some additional specializations of Discrete Coverages, and also some "compact" encoded versions.
Documented in OGC 06-188

Extensions to ISO 19107 Spatial Schema (implemented as GML Geometry schema), primarily dealing with simplified representations of some simple solids, surfaces and curves.
Documented in OGC 07-001
A subset of the 3D geometries from the gml:_Solid substitution group, not including CompositeSolid, and adding the XMML SimpleSolid group
A subset of the 1D geometries from the gml:_Curve substitution group, not including CompositeCurve, and adding the simplified XMML LineByVector
A subset of the 2D geometries from the gml:AbstractSurface substitution group.
A subset of the 2D geometries from the gml:_Surface substitution group, not including CompositeSurface, and adding the simplified XMML PlaneByVector

Extensions to ISO 19123 CV packages, primarily adding some additional specializations of Discrete Coverages, and also some "compact" encoded versions.
Documented in OGC 06-188
Classes representing compact implementations of discrete coverages.

Proposed additional specializations of CV_DiscreteCoverage.
CV_DiscreteCoverage is a subclass of CV_Coverage that returns a single record of values for any direct position within a single geometric object in its spatiotemporal domain.

Proposed additional specializations of CV_DiscreteCoverage.
CV_DiscreteCoverage is a subclass of CV_Coverage that returns a single record of values for any direct position within a single geometric object in its spatiotemporal domain.
time-instant coverage which samples a property of the feature of interest at different times
Not strictly a Coverage according to the definition in ISO 19123, since the domain objects are not geometrys.
coverage whose domain elements contain references to objects encoded elsewhere, which provide the sampling geometry of the feature of interest
Classes representing compact implementations of discrete coverages.
CV_DiscreteCoverage is a subclass of CV_Coverage that returns a single record of values for any direct position within a single geometric object in its spatiotemporal domain.
Classes corresponding to types and elements provided by GML that do not simply implement existing ISO 19100 classes from the Harmonized Model. See ISO 19136 Annex D.3.
Stub class representing collections of definitions. Implemented by gml:Dictionary.

Abstract class representing all classes stereotyped <<ObjectType>> i.e. classes that represent objects with identity that may be externally referenced. Implemented by gml:AbstractGML (gml 3.2) or gml:_GML (earlier versions).

Abstract class representing all classes stereotyped <<FeatureType>> i.e. classes that realize GF_FeatureType, representing features of all types from all application schemas. This class may be used as a "wildcard" when it is necessary to refer to a feature of any type.
N.B. Any class stereotyped <<FeatureType>> is implicitly substitutable for AnyFeature.
Implemented by gml:AbstractFeature (gml 3.2) or gml:_Feature (earlier versions).
The feature-of-interest is the identifiable object that carries the property whose value is being observed.
Pointer to an observation that provides an estimate of a property value

The featureOfInterest is a feature of any type (ISO 19109, ISO 19101), which is a representation of the observation target, being the real-world object regarding which the observation is made, such as a specimen, station, tract, mountain, pixel, etc. The spatial properties (location) of this feature of interest are typically of most interest for spatial analysis of the observation result.

A sampling feature must be associated with one or more other features through an association role sampledFeature. This association records the intention of the sample design. The target of this association will often be a domain feature.
Examples: a sounding typically samples a water- or atmospheric-column; a well samples an aquifer; a tissue specimen samples a part of an organism

A SamplingFeature must be associated with one or more other features through an association role sampledFeature. This association records the intention of the sample design. The target of this association will often be a domain feature.
Stub definition class. Implemented by gml:Definition.
